descriptive_long.solution:
Denote the series by $totalsum$, and let $coeffn = 3^{colidx}/colidx$.  Similarly, set $coeffm = 3^{rowidx}/rowidx$.  Note that
\begin{align*}
 totalsum &= \sum_{rowidx=1}^{\infty} \sum_{colidx=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{coeffm\bigl(coeffm+coeffn\bigr)} \\[-4pt]
 &= \sum_{rowidx=1}^{\infty} \sum_{colidx=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{coeffn\bigl(coeffm+coeffn\bigr)},
\end{align*}
where the second equality follows by interchanging $rowidx$ and $colidx$.  Thus
\begin{align*}
 2\,totalsum &= \sum_{rowidx} \sum_{colidx} \left( \frac{1}{coeffm\bigl(coeffm+coeffn\bigr)} + \frac{1}{coeffn\bigl(coeffm+coeffn\bigr)} \right) \\[-4pt]
 &= \sum_{rowidx} \sum_{colidx} \frac{1}{coeffm\,coeffn} \\[-4pt]
 &= \left( \sum_{colidx=1}^{\infty} \frac{colidx}{3^{colidx}} \right)^{2}.
\end{align*}
But
\[
 \sum_{colidx=1}^{\infty} \frac{colidx}{3^{colidx}} \,=\, \frac{3}{4}
\]
since, for example, it is $genfun'(1)$, where
\[
 genfun(inputvar)=\sum_{colidx=0}^{\infty} \frac{inputvar^{colidx}}{3^{colidx}}=\frac{3}{3-inputvar}.
\]
Consequently, $totalsum = 9/32$.}

kernel_variant.solution:
Step 1 - Rewrite the summand in a symmetric form.  
Put  
\[
a_{k}\;=\;\frac{11^{\,k}}{k^{3}}, \qquad
\varepsilon_{k}=(-1)^{k}\quad(k\ge 1).
\]
Then
\[
\frac{m^{6}\,n^{3}}{11^{\,m}\bigl(n^{3}\,11^{\,m}+m^{3}\,11^{\,n}\bigr)}
=\frac{1}{a_{m}\bigl(a_{m}+a_{n}\bigr)},
\]
so the required series can be written as  
\[
S=\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\;\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}
\varepsilon_{m}\varepsilon_{n}\;
\frac{1}{a_{m}\bigl(a_{m}+a_{n}\bigr)}.
\tag{1}
\]

Step 2 - Use the classical two-term identity  
\[
\frac{1}{x(x+y)}+\frac{1}{y(x+y)}=\frac{1}{xy}\qquad(x,y>0).
\]
Writing (1) and the same expression with the roles of \(m,n\) interchanged and adding, we obtain
\[
2S
=\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}
\varepsilon_{m}\varepsilon_{n}\;
\frac{1}{a_{m}a_{n}}
=\Bigl(\,\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\varepsilon_{k}\frac{1}{a_{k}}\Bigr)^{2}.
\tag{2}
\]

Step 3 - The single alternating series.  
Because \(a_{k}=11^{\,k}/k^{3}\),
\[
\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\varepsilon_{k}\frac{1}{a_{k}}
=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}(-1)^{k}\frac{k^{3}}{11^{\,k}}
=:T.
\]

To evaluate \(T\) set \(z:=-\tfrac1{11}\) and recall the identity
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n^{3}z^{n}
=\frac{z\,(1+4z+z^{2})}{(1-z)^{4}}\qquad(|z|<1).
\]
Substituting \(z=-\tfrac1{11}\) gives
\[
\begin{aligned}
T
&= \frac{-\tfrac1{11}\,\bigl(1+4(-\tfrac1{11})+(-\tfrac1{11})^{2}\bigr)}
{\bigl(1-(-\tfrac1{11})\bigr)^{4}}
= \frac{-\tfrac1{11}\left(1-\tfrac4{11}+\tfrac1{121}\right)}
{\left(\tfrac{12}{11}\right)^{4}}  \\[4pt]
&=\frac{-\tfrac1{11}\cdot\frac{78}{121}}{\frac{20736}{14641}}
=\frac{-78}{1331}\cdot\frac{14641}{20736}
=-\,\frac{78\cdot 11}{20736}
=-\,\frac{858}{20736}
=-\,\frac{143}{3456}.
\end{aligned}
\]

Step 4 - Finish the computation.  
By (2) we have
\[
2S=T^{2}=\Bigl(-\tfrac{143}{3456}\Bigr)^{2}
=\frac{20449}{11\,943\,936},
\qquad\Longrightarrow\qquad
S=\frac{20449}{23\,887\,872}.
\]

The fraction is already in lowest terms, so the required value is  

\[
\boxed{\displaystyle S=\frac{20449}{23\,887\,872}}.
\]

